**********************************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Wed 12 Jan 2022
Source: OIE-WAHIS 2022 [edited]
https://wahis.oie.int/#/report-info?reportId=46448


SARS-CoV-2 in animals (inf. with), Slovenia
-------------------------------------------
Summary
Report type: immediate notification
Started: 4 Jan 2022
Ended: 5 Jan 2022
Date of confirmation of the event: 5 Jan 2022
Reason for notification: emerging disease
Causal agent: SARS-CoV-2
Morbidity: 100%
Mortality: -
Zoonotic potential: yes
Zoonotic potential description: ferret is living as a pet animal in a household.
This event pertains to a defined zone within the country.

Outbreak location: Ljubljana, City Municipality of Ljubljana
Started on: 4 Jan 2022
Ended on: 5 Jan 2022
Epidemiological unit: Other
Total animals affected:
Species / Susceptible / Cases / Deaths / Killed and disposed of / Slaughtered or killed for commercial use / Vaccinated
Mustelidae / 1 / 1 / 0 / 0 / 0 / 0
Affected population description: ferret (pet animal) with clinical signs

Epidemiology
Source of the outbreak(s) or origin of infection: Unknown or inconclusive

Diagnostic test results
Laboratory name and type / Species / Outbreaks / Test / Test result date / Result
National Veterinary Institute, University of Ljubljana, Veterinary faculty National Laboratory (National Laboratory) / Mustelidae / 1 / Real-time reverse transcription polymerase chain reaction (rRT-PCR) / 5 Jan 2022 / positive

[The location of the outbreak can be seen on the interactive map included in the OIE report at the source URL above]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED

["People who are suspected or confirmed to be infected with SARS-CoV-2 should restrict contact with mammalian animals, including pets, just like they would with people during their illness.

"Animals suspected or confirmed to be infected with SARS-CoV-2 should remain separated from other animals and humans while infected.

"Biosecurity and hygiene measures are key to preventing transmission of SARS-CoV-2".

Source: https://www.oie.int/app/uploads/2021/11/en-factsheet-sars-cov-2-20211025.pdf. - Mod CRD

